        "text": "*[Bug 19012] foreign::write.foreign() generates incorrect SAS INPUT statement for character variables*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19012>\n\n--- Comment #5 from Troy Hernandez (<mailto:troy@cornball.ai|troy@cornball.ai>) ---\nFollowing up on whether this behavior should be considered a bug or merely\ncosmetic.\n\nIn SAS list input, the `$` modifier is the standard inline declaration that a\nvariable is character (see SAS DATA step documentation). A preceding `LENGTH`\nstatement can also establish type, but this creates a dependency between\nseparate parts of the generated program: the correctness of the `INPUT`\nspecification relies on earlier code remaining present.\n\nThis distinction matters in practice because one can reuse only the `INPUT`\nspecification generated by `write.foreign()` inside an existing DATA step\nrather than executing the generated SAS program verbatim. For example, when\nintegrating imports into an existing ETL pipeline that already defines the\ntarget dataset and file location. In such workflows the `LENGTH` block can be\nomitted:\n\n```\ndata work.newdata;\n  infile \"\/path\/df.txt\" dsd;\n  input a b c $;\nrun;\n\n```\n\nHere SAS interprets `a` as numeric (no `$`, and no prior `LENGTH` declaration).\nWhen the exported data contain character values such as `\"x\"` and `\"y\"`, SAS\nreports:\n\n```\nNOTE: Invalid data for a in line 1.\n\n```\n\nand the step fails under stricter pipeline settings.\n\nThe generated `INPUT` statement is not self-contained with respect to variable\ntype declaration. The omission of `$` can therefore affect correctness when the\nspecification is reused in realistic SAS workflows, rather than representing a\npurely stylistic difference.",
