        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19012] foreign::write.foreign() generates incorrect SAS INPUT statement for character variables*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19012>\n\n--- Comment #6 from Elin Waring (<mailto:elin.waring@gmail.com|elin.waring@gmail.com>) ---\nShort version: The current function generates a LENGTH statement.\n\n*Explanation*\n\nSAS types the variables based on information available when the variable is\nfirst referenced. The $ in the INPUT statement will only have an effect when\nthe variable has not already been defined.  You can even place a $ after a\nvariable that as already defined as numeric and it will have no effect.\n\nIn this example A and C are character.  A’s length is set to $20 and B’s to 8. \nAnd SAS will default C’s length to $8 because of the $ in the INPUT statement.\n\ndata one ;\n  length a $20 b 8;\n  input a b $ c $;\ncards;\n1 2 3\n;\n\nThe comment 5 example data step does NOT include the LENGTH statement that the\nforeign package generates. So it is not a valid comparison. \n\nThe changes I am working on will remove the LENGTH statement and instead add\nin-line informats with the : modifier  in the INPUT statement to give the SAS\ncomplier the information in needs to set the proper length for the character\nvariables.  That method would be more useful in his proposed scenario of a user\ntaking only the INPUT statement and trying to reuse it.\n\ninput a :$20. b c :$8. ;",
        "username": "r-bugs notifier",
        "icons": {
            "emoji": ":robot_face:"
        },
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1772555151.455459",
        "bot_id": "B06769YJX9Q",
        "app_id": "A024R9PQM",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "xZ0",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "[Bug 19012] foreign::write.foreign() generates incorrect SAS INPUT statement for character variables",
                                "style": {
                                    "bold": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19012"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\n--- Comment #6 from Elin Waring ("
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "mailto:elin.waring@gmail.com",
                                "text": "elin.waring@gmail.com"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ") ---\nShort version: The current function generates a LENGTH statement.\n\n"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Explanation",
                                "style": {
                                    "bold": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nSAS types the variables based on information available when the variable is\nfirst referenced. The $ in the INPUT statement will only have an effect when\nthe variable has not already been defined.  You can even place a $ after a\nvariable that as already defined as numeric and it will have no effect.\n\nIn this example A and C are character.  A’s length is set to $20 and B’s to 8. \nAnd SAS will default C’s length to $8 because of the $ in the INPUT statement.\n\ndata one ;\n  length a $20 b 8;\n  input a b $ c $;\ncards;\n1 2 3\n;\n\nThe comment 5 example data step does NOT include the LENGTH statement that the\nforeign package generates. So it is not a valid comparison. \n\nThe changes I am working on will remove the LENGTH statement and instead add\nin-line informats with the : modifier  in the INPUT statement to give the SAS\ncomplier the information in needs to set the proper length for the character\nvariables.  That method would be more useful in his proposed scenario of a user\ntaking only the INPUT statement and trying to reuse it.\n\ninput a :$20. b c :$8. ;"
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
